  "local_port": 56812,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I remove the HTC One X System folder, which still appears on my Windows 7 list of devices?",
  "response": "If you see an \"HTC One X System folder\" listed in your Windows 7 devices and you want to remove it, it\u2019s likely a leftover entry from when the phone was connected to your computer. Here\u2019s how you can remove it:\n\n### **1. Update or Reinstall the HTC Drivers**\n   - **Uninstall HTC Drivers:**\n     1. Go to **Control Panel** > **Programs and Features**.\n     2. Look for any HTC-related drivers or software (e.g., HTC Sync Manager, HTC Drivers).\n     3. Uninstall them.\n   - **Reinstall HTC Drivers:**\n     1. Visit the [HTC website](https://www.htc.com) and download the latest HTC Sync Manager or drivers for your device.\n     2. Install the software, then reconnect your HTC One X to see if the issue is resolved.\n\n### **2. Use the Device Manager to Remove the Device**\n   - **Open Device Manager:**\n     1. Press `Windows + R`, type `devmgmt.msc`, and press Enter.\n   - **Look for the HTC One X:**\n     1. Expand categories like **Portable Devices**, **Other Devices**, or **Universal Serial Bus controllers**.\n     2. If you see your HTC One X listed, right-click it and select **Uninstall device**.\n     3. Check the box to **Delete the driver software for this device** (if available).\n     4. Click **Uninstall**.\n\n### **3. Clear Residual USB Device Entries**\n   - **Run a Command to Clear Residual Entries:**\n     1. Open Command Prompt as an administrator (press `Windows + R`, type `cmd`, and press `Ctrl + Shift + Enter`).\n     2. Run the following command to remove hidden or ghosted devices:\n        ```cmd\n        set devmgr_show_nonpresent_devices=1\n        start devmgmt.msc\n        ```\n     3. In the Device Manager window, go to **View** > **Show hidden devices**.\n     4. Look for any grayed-out or ghosted entries of your HTC One X under **Portable Devices** or **Universal Serial Bus controllers**.\n     5. Right-click and uninstall any leftover entries.\n\n### **4. Restart Your Computer**\n   - After completing the above steps, restart your computer. The HTC One X System folder should no longer appear.\n\n### **5. Disable Autorun for Removable Drives (Optional)**\n   - If the issue persists, it might be related to autorun settings. To disable autorun:\n     1. Press `Windows + R`, type `gpedit.msc`, and press Enter.\n     2. Navigate to **Computer Configuration** > **Administrative Templates** > **Windows Components** > **AutoPlay Policies**.\n     3. Double-click **Turn off Autoplay**, enable it, and select **All drives**.\n     4. Click **OK**.\n\n### **6. Check for Third-Party Software**\n   - If you\u2019ve used third-party software for managing your HTC One X (e.g., file explorer tools), uninstall or update them.\n\nIf the issue persists after these steps, it could be a deeper system issue, and you may need to check for Windows updates or perform a system file check (`sfc /scannow` in Command Prompt). Let me know if you need further assistance!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
